% =======================================================================
%  HIGHLIGHTS  (Elsevier JAS requirement: 3 to 5 bullets, <=85 chars each)
% =======================================================================
\noindent\textbf{Highlights}
\begin{itemize}\setlength\itemsep{0pt}
  \item Geometric-null binomial is the test matched to harmonic-proximity hypotheses.
  \item Rayleigh concentration and binomial proximity enrichment can dissociate.
  \item Dissociation demonstrated on the UNESCO dome/stupa corpus ($N=\circTwoSampNDome{}$).
  \item Worked example: Wiki+OSM Fisher $\chi^2(4)=\geoFisherNcAChi{}$, $p\geoFisherNcAP{}$, Tier~A, excluding domes.
  \item Max statistic anchor sweep correction yields marginal $p = \anchorMaxPermP{}$.
\end{itemize}

\bigskip

\begin{abstract}
This paper addresses a mismatch between test and hypothesis in spatial periodicity
analysis. The Rayleigh statistic measures mean phase concentration at period $T$,
whereas a repeated-line grid hypothesis predicts thresholded proximity to any
harmonic longitude. These two summaries can dissociate within the same corpus.
The methods contribution is the geometric-null binomial framework:
(i)~define phases $\theta_i = 2\pi((\lambda_i-\lambda_0)\bmod T)/T$;
(ii)~compute harmonic deviation $\delta_i = \min(r_i, T-r_i)$;
(iii)~test the count of sites with $\delta_i \leq d$ against the geometric null $p_0 = 2d/T$;
(iv)~combine across independently assembled corpora via Fisher's method; and
(v)~apply an anchor sweep correction based on a max statistic when the anchor requires validation.
A period sweep of the UNESCO dome/stupa corpus ($N = \circTwoSampNDome{}$) demonstrates
the dissociation between Rayleigh concentration and proximity enrichment. Rayleigh is
significant at three periods that lack proximity enrichment, while the $3\degr$
period shows proximity enrichment with non-significant Rayleigh.
Applied to three hemispherical-monument corpora at the $3\degr$ period and
${\sim}35.25\degr$E Levantine corridor phase, the worked example finds consistent
corpus-level proximity enrichment. The result is invariant within the band, so any
longitude on the same grid within ${\pm}\AppThreshDeg\degr$ of this phase, including
Jerusalem and Mount Gerizim at $\GerizimLon\degr$E, produces identical proximity
counts. The two-corpus combination that excludes the dome corpus (Wikidata + OSM) gives
$\chi^2(4) = \geoFisherNcAChi{}$, $p\geoFisherNcAP{}$ at Tier~A (threshold $\pm 0.10 \times T$).
A correction based on a max statistic sweep over \anchorSweepNanchors{} trial longitudes
yields $p = \anchorMaxPermP{}$ after anchor correction (marginal), indicating that
results conditional on the chosen frame cannot be treated as unconditional; the marginal
corrected $p$ raises the possibility that anchor selection is doing meaningful work in the result. Following \citet{silva2020statistical}, all results are treated as
statistical descriptions of spatial structure; questions of mechanism and historical
transmission require independent evidence.
\end{abstract}

\bigskip
\noindent\textbf{Keywords:}
spatial statistics, circular statistics, harmonic proximity,
binomial geometric null, monument distribution, archaeoastronomy

\bigskip

\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:introduction}

Do monuments cluster near specific longitude intervals? The question
recurs in the archaeoastronomical and archaeogeographic literature,
usually motivated by observational coincidences involving sacred sites,
trade corridors, or cosmographic traditions. This paper focuses on
\emph{hemispherical monuments}, defined here as structures whose principal form is a
rounded or mounded mass, including Buddhist stupas, corbelled tholos
tombs, and domed shrines, as a corpus for testing
longitude-grid hypotheses. This broader question has also been
criticized on grounds of investigator-assembled site lists,
insufficient correction for multiple comparisons, and lack of
independent replication
\citep{williamson1983leylines,freeman1976,kendall1974}. These
concerns motivate a stricter separation between statistical detection
and archaeological explanation. Alongside these critiques, this paper raises the
complementary issue of matching tests to hypotheses. The standard
circular-statistical tool used in this literature measures a
different quantity from the one predicted by a repeated-line grid
hypothesis.

The tool in question is the Rayleigh statistic $R$. In its
circular-statistical form, Rayleigh's mean-resultant test is a standard
test of departure from uniformity toward a single preferred direction
on the circle \citep{rayleigh1919,fisher1993circular,mardiajupp2000},
most commonly encountered in archaeology and skyscape work in orientation
and azimuth analysis \citep{magli2016,silva2020statistical}. Here it
becomes relevant because longitudes can be folded modulo a candidate
period $T$: $R$ then measures whether the folded phases concentrate
toward one direction.

This is a useful diagnostic, but only a partial answer to the
repeated-line question. A grid-placement hypothesis predicts that
sites fall near longitudes $\lambda_0, \lambda_0 + T, \lambda_0 + 2T,
\ldots$. Under modulo-$T$ phase mapping these harmonics collapse to a
common phase, so an ideal grid-aligned corpus would produce strong
Rayleigh concentration. In real geographically clustered corpora,
however, Rayleigh concentration and thresholded harmonic proximity can
dissociate: a dominant off-harmonic cluster can produce significant
Rayleigh concentration, while a corpus with many near-harmonic sites
plus substantial off-harmonic mass can produce binomial enrichment
without significant Rayleigh $R$. A non-significant Rayleigh result
therefore does not rule out harmonic proximity, and a significant
Rayleigh result does not by itself establish proximity to repeated
longitude lines. The two statistics are complementary; they answer
related but distinct questions.

The directly matched test for ``sites cluster near harmonics'' is
straightforward. Under a uniform longitude model, the expected fraction
of longitudes falling within $\pm d\degr$ of any harmonic of period $T$
is $p_0 = 2d/T$. This is the \emph{geometric null}. In clustered
corpora it remains a useful geometric benchmark, but the resulting
$p$-values are interpreted here as corpus-level proximity enrichment
rather than counts of independent placement decisions.

This paper develops that matched test and uses the monument data as a
worked methodological example. Under a fixed period, fixed corridor phase,
fixed proximity thresholds, and fixed operational corpora, the
geometric-null binomial test estimates whether more sites fall near
harmonic longitudes than expected from the geometric coverage of the
threshold bands. Rayleigh statistics are retained as complementary
circular diagnostics, and the period sweep is used to show when phase
concentration and thresholded harmonic proximity agree or dissociate.
The empirical application illustrates corpus-level proximity enrichment
at the fixed $3\degr$ period and ${\sim}35.25\degr$E Levantine corridor
phase. Following \citet{silva2020statistical}, this is treated
throughout as statistical description of spatial structure in an
open-data worked example; historical, cultural, or geographic
explanation is a separate interpretive task requiring independent
evidence.

\section{Rayleigh Concentration and Harmonic Proximity:\\
Complementary but Distinct Statistics}
\label{sec:rayleigh_vs_binom}

\subsection{Why the Two Statistics Can Dissociate}

Let $\lambda_1, \ldots, \lambda_N$ be site longitudes and $T$ a
candidate grid period with anchor $\lambda_0$. Define phases by
$\theta_i = 2\pi((\lambda_i - \lambda_0) \bmod T)/T$, and the
Rayleigh statistic by

\[
R = \left| \frac{1}{N} \sum_{i=1}^{N} e^{\imath\theta_i} \right|,
\]
where $\imath = \sqrt{-1}$ (complex exponential; equivalently,
$e^{\imath\theta} = \cos\theta + \imath\sin\theta$, so $R$ is the length of the
mean of the unit vectors $(\cos\theta_i, \sin\theta_i)$).

A key property of this transformation is that sites near \emph{any}
harmonic of $T$ all map to the same phase $\theta \approx 0$ under the
modulo-$T$ reduction. This includes sites near $\lambda_0$,
$\lambda_0 + T$, $\lambda_0 + 2T$, and so on, because
$(\lambda_0 + kT - \lambda_0) \bmod T = 0$ for any integer $k$.
Under ideal conditions, in which all sites fall exactly on a harmonic,
$R$ would equal 1. The modulo-$T$ phase map therefore does not, by
itself, produce multiple phase classes: harmonics collapse to one class,
not many.

The Rayleigh test and the binomial proximity test can nevertheless
dissociate because they aggregate cross-site information differently.

\emph{What Rayleigh measures.} $R$ is the length of the mean phasor. It
is sensitive to whether a \emph{single direction} on the unit circle
predominates after averaging over the full corpus. In a geographically
clustered corpus, a single dominant geographic cluster can produce
large $R$ at period $T$ simply because that cluster's longitude maps to
a concentrated phase at that particular $T$, regardless of whether the
cluster is harmonically proximate. This is a generic property of
clustered data on the unit circle; it can produce significant $R$ at
periods that have no interpretation as harmonic proximity.

\emph{What the binomial measures.} The binomial proximity test counts
the number of sites whose deviation from the nearest harmonic falls
within a threshold $d$, written as $\#\{i : \delta_i \leq d\}$. With
$r_i = ((\lambda_i - \lambda_0) \bmod T)$ and
$\delta_i = \min(r_i, T - r_i)$, this count is independent of the mean
phase direction. Sites far from
harmonics (large $\delta_i$) contribute zero to the binomial count
regardless of whether they push $R$ up or down. Conversely, a corpus
can show significant binomial enrichment even when many off-harmonic
sites keep the mean phasor small.

\emph{Complementarity.} The two tests ask complementary questions.
Rayleigh asks whether one phase direction dominates. The binomial asks
whether more sites lie within a fixed reporting threshold of a harmonic
than the uniform null predicts. In a real corpus these can agree or disagree,
depending on the balance between harmonically proximate sites,
off-harmonic sites, and the geographic clustering structure of the
corpus. A non-significant Rayleigh result does not rule out harmonic
proximity; a significant Rayleigh result does not establish harmonic
proximity unless the phase concentration is verified to coincide with
a harmonic. Relying on Rayleigh alone to evaluate a repeated-line
hypothesis can therefore produce false positives at cluster-dominated
periods and miss genuine proximity enrichment when near-harmonic sites
coexist with substantial off-harmonic mass.

\subsection{Empirical Demonstration: Period Sweep Dissociation}

The following demonstration uses the UNESCO keyword-matched dome/stupa
corpus described fully in Section~\ref{sec:data}.
Table~\ref{tab:rayleigh_vs_binom} illustrates the dissociation
concretely ($N = \circTwoSampNDome{}$). The full sweep of 46 candidate periods
(1.5\degr{} to 6.0\degr{} in 0.1\degr{} steps) is available in the
supplementary audit; four representative periods are shown here to
illustrate the qualitatively distinct outcomes. Both tests use the Tier-A threshold
($\pm 0.10 \times T$, geometric null $p_0 = \NullRateA{}$; tiers defined in
Section~\ref{sec:tiers}); finer-threshold tiers (A$+$, A$++$) are reported
in the primary results.

\begin{table}[ht]
\centering
\caption{Rayleigh concentration vs.\ Tier~A binomial proximity
enrichment at four representative periods drawn from a full sweep of
46 candidate periods (1.5\degr{} to 6.0\degr{} in 0.1\degr{} steps;
complete sweep tables in supplementary audit). These four periods
span the full range of dissociation outcomes, including three periods
with significant Rayleigh concentration but no proximity enrichment, and
one period with proximity enrichment but non-significant Rayleigh concentration.
UNESCO dome corpus ($N = \circTwoSampNDome{}$, corridor phase ${\sim}35.25\degr$E).
Tier-A threshold $= 0.10 \times T$; geometric null $p_0 = \NullRateA{}$.
Sig symbols: $^{*}p < 0.05$, $^{**}p < 0.01$, ns = not significant.}
\label{tab:rayleigh_vs_binom}
\small
\begin{tabular}{rlcrrrl}
\toprule
Period & Rayleigh $p$ & Sig & Tier-A hits & Expected
       & Binom.\ $p$ & Sig \\
\midrule
$2.4\degr$ & \sweepRayleighPTwoFour{}  & \sweepRayleighSigTwoFour{}
           & \sweepHitsTwoFour{}  & \sweepExpectedTwoFour{}
           & \sweepBinomPTwoFour{}  & \sweepBinomSigTwoFour{} \\
$3.0\degr$ & \sweepRayleighPThreeZero{} & \sweepRayleighSigThreeZero{}
           & \sweepHitsThreeZero{} & \sweepExpectedThreeZero{}
           & \sweepBinomPThreeZero{} & \textbf{\sweepBinomSigThreeZero{}} \\
$3.5\degr$ & \sweepRayleighPThreeFive{} & \sweepRayleighSigThreeFive{}
           & \sweepHitsThreeFive{} & \sweepExpectedThreeFive{}
           & \sweepBinomPThreeFive{} & \sweepBinomSigThreeFive{} \\
$3.6\degr$ & \sweepRayleighPThreeSix{}  & \sweepRayleighSigThreeSix{}
           & \sweepHitsThreeSix{}  & \sweepExpectedThreeSix{}
           & \sweepBinomPThreeSix{}  & \sweepBinomSigThreeSix{} \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

The dissociation is clear. Rayleigh is significant at
$2.4\degr$, $3.5\degr$, and $3.6\degr$, and non-significant at
$3.0\degr$. The binomial proximity test is significant only at
$3.0\degr$. A researcher relying on Rayleigh alone to evaluate the
repeated-line hypothesis would flag periods that carry no proximity
enrichment, and would overlook the period with the clearest proximity
structure. Using the two tests together avoids this.

The pattern is consistent with the mechanism described above. At
$2.4\degr$, $3.5\degr$, and $3.6\degr$, one geographic cluster
dominates the phase distribution, producing concentrated $R$ without
harmonic proximity enrichment. At $3.0\degr$, many sites fall near the
harmonic class, but substantial off-harmonic mass keeps the mean phasor
small; the binomial test correctly registers the thresholded per-site
proximity counts. Rayleigh and the binomial measure genuinely
different aspects of the data; neither is wrong, but only the binomial
directly answers the question ``do sites fall near harmonics?''

A broader candidate-period survey of the dome/stupa corpus
(1.5\degr{} to 6.0\degr{} in 0.1\degr{} steps, 46 periods; four
representative periods shown in Table~\ref{tab:rayleigh_vs_binom})
finds the dominant binomial proximity peak at $3\degr$ ($p = \sweepBinomPThreeZero{}$);
selected nearby non-harmonic spacings ($1.8\degr$, $2.1\degr$, $2.7\degr$,
$3.3\degr$) are non-significant in the same sweep. This motivates $3\degr$ as the
primary period for the cross-corpus analysis in Section~\ref{sec:results}.

The dissociation also appears in the full UNESCO cultural corpus ($N = 1{,}011$
sites with coordinates, including non-dome cultural sites). At $T = 3\degr$,
Rayleigh remains non-significant ($p = 0.60$), while binomial proximity
enrichment is significant across all three tier thresholds (Tier~A:
$p = 0.025$; Tier~A$^+$: $p = 0.001$; Tier~A$^{++}$: $p = 0.010$).
Because this corpus includes the dome sites that motivated the period, it does
not constitute independent validation. It does show that the dissociation
between Rayleigh and binomial results is not an artifact of the restricted dome
vocabulary.

\begin{figure}[ht]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.92\textwidth]{figures/fig_period_sweep.pdf}
\caption{Period sweep of the UNESCO dome/stupa corpus ($N = \circTwoSampNDome{}$):
$-\log_{10}(p)$ for the binomial proximity-enrichment test (blue; threshold
$\pm 0.10 \times T$) and the permutation Rayleigh test (orange) across 46 candidate
periods (1.5\degr{} to 6.0\degr{} in 0.1\degr{} steps); anchor ${\approx}35.25\degr$E.
