highlights the dominant proximity peak; Rayleigh is non-significant at this period,
illustrating the dissociation between Rayleigh and binomial results.}
\label{fig:period_sweep}
\end{figure}

A Monte Carlo spacing test (\simNperms{} permutations, dome label
shuffle) across \mcNcandidates{} candidate spacings from 0.5\degr{} to 15\degr{}
(full list in supplementary audit) finds the observed count of
\mcDomeNsigObs{} significant spacings marginal ($p \approx \mcDomePObsGe{}$).
Three of the four significant spacings (6\degr{}, 8\degr{}, 12\degr{}) are
multiples of 3\degr{} and their hits are fully accounted for by the
3\degr{} harmonic structure; the $3\degr$ spacing is the only one whose
significance is not explained by overlap with another spacing's nodes.

\section{The Geometric-Null Binomial Framework}
\label{sec:framework}

\subsection{The Geometric Null}

For a grid of period $T$ anchored at $\lambda_0$, define the
anchor-relative remainder and nearest-harmonic deviation as

\[
r_i = ((\lambda_i - \lambda_0) \bmod T), \qquad
\delta_i = \min(r_i, T-r_i).
\]

A site falls within tier threshold $d$ if $\delta_i \leq d$. Under a
uniform longitude model, the expected fraction of longitudes satisfying
that inequality is $p_0 = 2d/T$. In clustered corpora this remains a
useful geometric benchmark; the resulting $p$-values are interpreted as
corpus-level proximity enrichment rather than counts of independent
placement decisions. Declustering is not applied: it requires an
arbitrary linkage scale with no principled stopping point, and
geographic clustering here reflects documented place-specific building
traditions rather than duplicate observations. The multi-corpus design provides the
structural safeguard: the three corpora are dominated by different
geographic nodes (the distributed Eurasian corridor for UNESCO, the
Java/Sumatra node for Wikidata, and crowd-sourced coverage density
across South and Southeast Asia for OSM), so no single cluster can
simultaneously account for enrichment across all three independently
assembled datasets. Two empirical checks indicate the result is not a
generic corridor artifact: the anchor sweep places the Levantine phase
at only the \anchorSweepPctile{}th percentile of all \anchorSweepNanchors{}
trial longitudes (Section~\ref{sec:results}), and the UNESCO Americas
sub-corpus shows no proximity enrichment at the Levantine phase
(A$+$ rate below the geometric null).

The two null models reported in Section~\ref{sec:results}
(Null~A: within-dome bootstrap; Null~B: same-footprint UNESCO background,
the discriminating comparison) provide complementary assessments of the
observed UNESCO proximity enrichment; they are discussed in
Section~\ref{sec:discussion}.

\subsection{Tier Classification}\label{sec:tiers}

We define three proximity thresholds as round fractions of the $T/2$
half-period ($1.5\degr$), calibrated to bracket the empirical natural
proximity scales of the corpora under study: the Old World Trade Routes
(OWTRAD; \citealt{ciolek2004owtrad}) Silk Road network (\naturalNullPctOwtrad\%), the UNESCO dome subset (\naturalNullPctDome\%), the full UNESCO
Cultural/Mixed corpus (\naturalNullPctFull\%), and the Wikidata stupa corpus (\naturalNullPctWiki\%).\footnote{These values are the peak-enrichment null rates from the multiscale window sweep
  (\texttt{analysis/\allowbreak{}unesco/\allowbreak{}multiscale\_combined\_p.py}); a standalone
  reproduction is provided in
  \texttt{supplementary/\allowbreak{}audit/\allowbreak{}tier\_calibration\_audit.py}.}
Each threshold corresponds to a geometric null rate $p_0 = 2d/T$
(A$++$ denotes the finest, strictest threshold; A the most lenient):

\begin{center}
\small
\begin{tabular}{lll}
\toprule
Tier & Threshold & Geometric null $p_0$ \\
\midrule
A$++$ & $\delta \leq \AppThreshDeg\degr$ ($\lesssim \AppThreshKm$~km equatorial) & \NullRateApp \\
A$+$  & $\delta \leq \ApThreshDeg\degr$  ($\lesssim \ApThreshKm$~km)             & \NullRateAp  \\
A     & $\delta \leq \ATierThreshDeg\degr$ ($\lesssim \ATierThreshKm$~km)        & \NullRateA   \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

Tier labels are descriptive shorthand; the primary test is always the
binomial. Because the thresholds are calibrated to the empirical proximity
scales of the corpora under study, data-adaptive threshold selection of
this kind may favor detecting enrichment at the chosen values; results
should be evaluated by the binomial statistics rather than the tier
labels themselves.

\subsection{Cross-Corpus Consistency via Fisher Combination}

For each corpus $c$ at tier $d$, a one-sided binomial test yields
$p_c$. Fisher's combination statistic $\chi^2 = -2\sum_c \ln p_c$,
referred to $\chi^2(2C)$ for $C$ corpora, summarizes whether the
directional excess is consistent across all corpora simultaneously.
Fisher's method formally assumes independent $p$-values. The three
corpora were assembled by distinct processes and their geographic
clusters are substantially non-overlapping, but they share historical
and geographic structure (Eurasian corridor, stupa tradition, public
data sources). The combined $p$-value is therefore used as a descriptive
consistency summary only; the individual corpus $p$-values are the
primary evidence, and the combination summarizes their direction rather
than providing a formal joint test with frequentist error guarantees.

The dome corpus period sweep identifies $3\degr$ as the dominant proximity
peak in that corpus; this motivates evaluating the independently assembled
corpora at the same period. Wikidata and OSM were evaluated at $3\degr$ without
any period sweep of those corpora. This asymmetry is verifiable from the
published code and audit files. Following \citet{silva2020statistical}, all
results are treated as statistical description of spatial structure; there is no
prior documentation of a $3\degr$ harmonic grid anchored to the Levantine
corridor, and these statistics do not constitute evidence for one absent
independent archaeological support. The two-corpus Fisher restricted to Wikidata
and OSM (reported in Table~\ref{tab:cross_corpus_geo} as ``Dome-excl.\
combined'') summarizes whether the same period shows consistent proximity
enrichment across independently assembled datasets.

\section{Data}
\label{sec:data}

\textbf{UNESCO dome/stupa subset ($N = \circTwoSampNDome{}$).}
The UNESCO World Heritage XML dataset \citep{unescowhc2024xml} contains
\NclusterTotal{} Cultural and Mixed inscribed sites. Seven morphological
keywords (stupa/stupas, tholos, dome/domed/domes, spherical) were
matched against site names, XML descriptions, and OUV text, yielding
$N = \circTwoSampNDome{}$ sites. All statistical tests use this
keyword-matched population.

\textbf{Wikidata Q180987 stupa corpus ($N = \npcNStupa{}$).}
All \textit{instance-of: stupa} (Q180987) items in the Wikidata
knowledge base, extracted via SPARQL query on the
\textit{instance-of: stupa} property. The corpus is
geographically dominated by the Java/Sumatra node, roughly from
${\sim}105\degr$E to ${\sim}115\degr$E, reflecting the documented historical density
of stupa construction around Borobudur \citep{miksic1990borobudur}.

\textbf{OSM stupa layer ($N = \osmStupaTotal{}$).}
OpenStreetMap features with tags \texttt{building=stupa},
\texttt{historic=stupa}, or \texttt{ruins=stupa}, assembled by
crowd-sourced tagging via Overpass API \citep{osmcontributors2024}.
Data \copyright{} OpenStreetMap contributors, available under the Open
Database Licence (ODbL~1.0; \url{https://opendatacommons.org/licenses/odbl/}).
The corpus is treated as a
co-primary dataset: it is assembled by a process entirely independent
of UNESCO and Wikidata curation, and OSM's coverage notes are a
property of the dataset as a whole rather than a limitation specific
to this application.

All three corpora were tested against the same fixed candidate
frame: period $3\degr$ and the ${\sim}35.25\degr$E Levantine corridor
phase. Because open datasets are publicly available, the frame is
treated uniformly as fixed for the present analysis across all three
corpora. The empirical application therefore functions as a
frame-specified spatial test.

\textbf{Candidate frame.}
The candidate reference phase is the ${\sim}35.25\degr$E Levantine corridor
phase, which emerged as the dominant proximity peak phase in the dome corpus
sweep described in Section~\ref{sec:rayleigh_vs_binom}; Wikidata and OSM were
evaluated at this phase without independent sweeps of their own.
The counts are invariant within the band. Any anchor longitude within
${\pm}\AppThreshDeg\degr$ of this phase, including Jerusalem at
\JerusalemLon\degr{}E, produces identical proximity counts, and the data
cannot distinguish between longitudes on the same grid within the same proximity tier.
The anchor is labeled by Mount Gerizim at \GerizimLon\degr{}E, a topographic
summit within the Levantine corridor absent from all monument corpora and not
derived from any external literature on longitude grids. It serves as a named
geographic coordinate for the interval under test; no substantive weight should
be attached to the choice of Gerizim over any other co-grid longitude within the
same proximity tier.

\section{Results}
\label{sec:results}

\subsection{Primary Result: Cross-Corpus Geometric-Null Test}

Table~\ref{tab:cross_corpus_geo} reports the primary statistical
results: one-sided binomial tests and Fisher combinations across all
three corpora.

