  & OSM stupas      & \geoOsmAppN{}  & \geoOsmAppHits{}  & \geoOsmAppExp{}  & \geoOsmAppEnr{}$\times$  & \geoOsmAppP{}  & \geoOsmAppSig{} \\
  & \multicolumn{7}{l}{\textit{All-3 Fisher $\chi^2(6) = \geoFisherAppChi{}$, nominal $p = \geoFisherAppP{}$}} \\
  & \multicolumn{7}{l}{\textit{Dome-excl.\ combined (Wiki+OSM) $\chi^2(4) = \geoFisherNcAppChi{}$, $p = \geoFisherNcAppP{}$, \geoFisherNcAppSig{}}} \\
\midrule
\multirow{5}{*}{A$+$ ($p_0{=}\NullRateAp{}$)}
  & UNESCO domes    & \geoDomeApN{}  & \geoDomeApHits{}  & \geoDomeApExp{}  & \geoDomeApEnr{}$\times$  & \geoDomeApP{}  & \geoDomeApSig{} \\
  & Wikidata stupas & \geoWikiApN{}  & \geoWikiApHits{}  & \geoWikiApExp{}  & \geoWikiApEnr{}$\times$  & \geoWikiApP{}  & \geoWikiApSig{} \\
  & OSM stupas      & \geoOsmApN{}   & \geoOsmApHits{}   & \geoOsmApExp{}   & \geoOsmApEnr{}$\times$   & \geoOsmApP{}   & \geoOsmApSig{} \\
  & \multicolumn{7}{l}{\textit{All-3 Fisher $\chi^2(6) = \geoFisherApChi{}$, nominal $p = \geoFisherApP{}$}} \\
  & \multicolumn{7}{l}{\textit{Dome-excl.\ combined (Wiki+OSM) $\chi^2(4) = \geoFisherNcApChi{}$, $p = \geoFisherNcApP{}$, \geoFisherNcApSig{}}} \\
\midrule
\multirow{5}{*}{A ($p_0{=}\NullRateA{}$)}
  & UNESCO domes    & \geoDomeAN{}   & \geoDomeAHits{}   & \geoDomeAExp{}   & \geoDomeAEnr{}$\times$   & \geoDomeAP{}   & \geoDomeASig{} \\
  & Wikidata stupas & \geoWikiAN{}   & \geoWikiAHits{}   & \geoWikiAExp{}   & \geoWikiAEnr{}$\times$   & \geoWikiAP{}   & \geoWikiASig{} \\
  & OSM stupas      & \geoOsmAN{}    & \geoOsmAHits{}    & \geoOsmAExp{}    & \geoOsmAEnr{}$\times$    & \geoOsmAP{}    & \geoOsmASig{} \\
  & \multicolumn{7}{l}{\textit{All-3 Fisher $\chi^2(6) = \geoFisherAChi{}$, nominal $p \geoFisherAPDisp{}$}} \\
  & \multicolumn{7}{l}{\textit{Dome-excl.\ combined (Wiki+OSM) $\chi^2(4) = \geoFisherNcAChi{}$, $p \geoFisherNcAP{}$, \geoFisherNcASig{}}} \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

In the worked example, all three corpora exceed the geometric null at every tier
despite substantially different geographic footprints and assembly
processes. Fisher combinations are reported as cross-corpus consistency
summaries (see Section~\ref{sec:framework} for the independence caveat).
The UNESCO A$++$ result shows the
largest individual fold-enrichment ($\geoDomeAppEnr{}\times$), reflecting the
distributed character of that corpus; Wikidata and OSM A$++$ results
are individually non-significant, reflecting cluster-level rather than
individual-site precision. The two-corpus combination restricted to Wikidata and OSM
(``Dome-excl.\ combined'') yields
$\chi^2(4) = \geoFisherNcAChi{}$, $p \geoFisherNcAP{}$ at Tier~A and $\chi^2(4) = \geoFisherNcApChi{}$,
$p = \geoFisherNcApP{}$ at Tier~A$+$; the Tier~A$++$ two-corpus combination is
non-significant ($p = \geoFisherNcAppP{}$). The all-three-corpus Tier~A Fisher
combination ($p \geoFisherAPDisp{}$) includes the dome corpus, which motivated
the period, and provides a less conservative cross-corpus summary than the dome-excluded combination.
All $p$-values are frame-conditional proximity-enrichment measures for the
fixed $3\degr$ period and ${\sim}35.25\degr$E Levantine corridor phase;
following \citet{silva2020statistical} they are statistical descriptions of
spatial structure, not evidence of historical placement. The $3\degr$ period
emerged as the dominant proximity peak in the dome corpus sweep
(Section~\ref{sec:rayleigh_vs_binom}); the three-corpus analysis
is the methodological demonstration that the same statistical pattern appears
consistently across independently assembled datasets at this period. A correction
based on a max statistic sweep (\anchorMaxPermNperms{} permutations over
\anchorSweepNanchors{} trial anchors) yields $p = \anchorMaxPermP{}$ after anchor
correction ($z = \anchorMaxPermZ{}$, marginal), indicating that results conditional
on the fixed frame should not be treated as unconditional; full details are in
Section~\ref{sec:discussion}.

\subsection{Supplementary Rayleigh Phase Concentration}

Rayleigh statistics are retained as complementary diagnostics for
comparability with prior literature. Table~\ref{tab:rayleigh_summary} reports them at
$T = 3\degr$. The full UNESCO
corpus shows no Rayleigh phase concentration ($R = \circConcUnescoR{}$,
perm-$p = \circConcUnescoP{}$, ns) at $T = 3\degr$, consistent with the proximity
pattern not being a generic circular-statistical property of the full heritage list. Watson's $U^2$ and Kuiper tests are retained as corroborating two-sample
diagnostics (not independent tests): both show that the dome/stupa phase
distribution differs detectably from the full UNESCO corpus
($p = \circWatsonPUnescoStupa{}$, $p = \circKuiperPUnescoStupa{}$ respectively).
Because any geographically concentrated subset will tend to differ from its
parent corpus in phase distribution, these results show concentration rather
than proximity enrichment per se; they are included for comparability with prior
literature that uses two-sample circular diagnostics as subset-specificity checks.

