\subsection{Negative Controls and Scope}

The OWTRAD Silk Road route network ($N = \npcNOwtrad{}$ nodes) does
not independently recover the monument phase in the Normalized Phasor
Consensus (NPC) test ($K = |\bar{u}_A \cdot \bar{u}_B|$, where
$\bar{u}_c$ is the normalized mean phasor of corpus $c$; $K=1$
indicates identical phase direction, $K=0$ orthogonal; full derivation
in Section~\ref{sec:anchor_concordance}; $K = \npcNegUnOwK{}$,
perm-$p = \npcNegUnOwPermP{}$, ns). Using the \NOwtradEdges{} edge midpoints as the proximity sample
(one value per route segment, non-deduplicated) is the most
conservative representation of the network; the binomial test is
non-significant at both tiers (A$++$: $p = \pOwtradMidApp{}$,
ns; A$+$: $p = \pOwtradMidAp{}$, ns). The route network therefore
shows no enrichment under either the directional or the per-segment
proximity test when each segment is counted once.

The UNESCO Americas sub-corpus ($N = \npcNAmericas{}$) shows A$+$
rate of \AmericasApRate\%, below the \NullRateAp{} geometric null, indicating
no proximity enrichment at the ${\sim}35.25\degr$E Levantine corridor
phase in the Western Hemisphere.

A type-matched geographic control uses the North American mound corpus
($N = \moundsN{}$): National Historic Landmark (NHL) and National
Register of Historic Places (NRHP)-registered earthen burial and
platform mounds assembled from the NPS National Register database with
coordinates resolved via Wikidata \citep{nps2024nrhp,wikidata2024}.
These are broadly mounded earthen structures used here as a geographically
distinct type control, located entirely in the Western Hemisphere outside
any connection to the ${\sim}35.25\degr$E Levantine corridor phase.
At the $3\degr$ period and ${\sim}35.25\degr$E Levantine corridor phase
the mounds corpus shows
no proximity enrichment at any tier:
A$++$: \moundsNApp{}/\moundsN{} (\moundsRateApp{}\%, null \NullRateApp{},
$p = \moundsPApp{}$, \moundsPAppSig{});
A$+$: \moundsNAp{}/\moundsN{} (\moundsRateAp{}\%, null \NullRateAp{},
$p = \moundsPAp{}$, \moundsPApSig{});
A: \moundsNA{}/\moundsN{} (\moundsRateA{}\%, null \NullRateA{},
$p = \moundsPA{}$, \moundsPASig{}).
All three tiers are at or below the geometric null.
This supports the methodological illustration that the Eurasian
pattern is geographically specific to the Eurasian corridor rather
than a generic outcome of applying the same harmonic-proximity test
to hemispherical monument corpora.

Null~B (same-footprint restricted draw, \simNperms{} trials) is the
discriminating comparison: does the dome/stupa subset show greater
harmonic proximity than the broader UNESCO background occupying the
same longitude footprint? This comparison is possible for the UNESCO
corpus because a larger parent population (the full UNESCO Cultural/Mixed
list, $N = \NclusterTotal{}$ sites) exists from which the dome/stupa
subset was selected. No equivalent parent population exists for the
Wikidata or OSM corpora, which are already operationally defined as
all stupa-tagged items; a same-footprint Null B comparison therefore
applies only to the UNESCO corpus. Three window widths were tested
(${\pm}2\degr$, ${\pm}5\degr$, ${\pm}10\degr$; Bonferroni
$\alpha_\mathrm{adj} = \nullBBonfAlpha{}$): the ${\pm}2\degr$ window gives
$p = \geoNullDomeRestrictedPtwo{}$; the ${\pm}5\degr$ window gives
$p = \geoNullDomeRestrictedPfive{}$; the ${\pm}10\degr$ window gives
$p = \geoNullDomeRestrictedPten{}$. All three windows survive
Bonferroni correction ($\alpha_\mathrm{adj} = \nullBBonfAlpha{}$),
illustrating subset-specific enrichment within the shared geography
across all window choices.\footnote{A within-dome bootstrap (Null~A,
\simNperms{} trials) resamples from the dome sites' own longitude
distribution; its expected hit rate is defined by the same geography
carrying the proximity enrichment, so it cannot serve as a
discriminating comparison. The observed A$++$ count is non-significant
under this null ($p = \geoNullDomeBootP{}$, ns), consistent with the pattern being
localized to dome-site geography rather than an artifact of the
comparison procedure.}

\subsection{Anchor Concordance}
\label{sec:anchor_concordance}

All three corpora recover the same ${\sim}35.25\degr$E Levantine
corridor phase. The Normalized Phasor Consensus statistic $K$ is
defined as $K = |\bar{u}_A \cdot \bar{u}_B|$, where $\bar{u}_c =
(\sum_k e^{\imath\theta_k^{(c)}})/|\sum_k e^{\imath\theta_k^{(c)}}|$
(unit complex numbers as in Section~\ref{sec:rayleigh_vs_binom}) is the
normalized mean phasor of corpus $c$ at the candidate period, and
$|\cdot|$ denotes the modulus of the dot product of two unit complex
numbers. The dot-product formulation is
preferred over the circular correlation coefficient
\citep[§8.3]{mardiajupp2000} because it compares phase
\emph{directions} only, stripping out amplitude information that is
irrelevant when corpora differ substantially in size and clustering:
$K = 1$ when the two corpora point to the same phase, $K = 0$ when
they are orthogonal. Its null distribution is estimated by
permutation throughout.
In the worked example,
$K \geq \npcDomeStupaK{}$ for all pairings of the three monument
corpora (Table~\ref{tab:npc_key}). The OSM + Wikidata pair
($K = \npcOsmStupaK{}$, perm-$p = \npcOsmStupaPermP{}$, ns) illustrates
the power limitation of two-corpus tests when both corpora share a
Southeast Asian geographic footprint: the high $K$ indicates strong phase
agreement, but the permutation null cannot be rejected with two corpora alone.
The three-corpus combination reaches
perm-$p = \npcOsmThreePermP{}$ with consensus anchor at
$\npcOsmThreeGridDeltaE\degr$ from $35\degr$E. The primary non-nested
two-corpus pair (Dome + Wikidata) is individually non-significant,
reflecting the limited power of a two-corpus permutation test: high $K$
indicates strong phase agreement, but two corpora alone cannot reject the
null that such agreement arises by chance. Significance emerges when the
independently assembled OSM corpus is added as a third data source, because
three corpora independently converging on the same phase is rare under the
permutation null even when individual pairs are underpowered. Negative controls show
$K$ drops sharply when the monument corpora are replaced with
geographic or route-network controls.

