\FloatBarrier
\section{Discussion}
\label{sec:discussion}

\subsection{The Methods Contribution}

The central methodological result is the separation between circular
phase concentration and thresholded harmonic proximity. Rayleigh $R$
describes whether the full phase distribution has a dominant mean
direction at period $T$; the geometric-null binomial describes whether
a corpus contains more sites within a stated operational distance of any
harmonic than expected from the fraction of longitude covered by those
bands. Because the two statistics weight off-harmonic observations
differently, they provide complementary information and can dissociate
within the same corpus. This makes Rayleigh a useful diagnostic for
phase structure and the geometric-null binomial the matched statistic
for thresholded proximity-to-harmonics claims. In Silva's terms, the
tests detect and describe structured features in the spatial data;
archaeological, historical, or geographic explanations for those
features remain interpretive questions to be evaluated with independent
evidence.

The analysis is a descriptive spatial test of harmonic proximity.
Geographic clustering is part of the documented corpus pattern, so
site-level binomial $p$-values describe corpus-level proximity
enrichment rather than independent cultural decisions. The geometric
null $p_0 = 2d/T$ gives a transparent expected hit fraction under
uniform longitude, and Fisher's method is used as a
cross-corpus consistency summary. This framework is applicable to any
spatial periodicity hypothesis of this form regardless of geographic
or cultural context.

\subsection{Interpretation of the Empirical Illustration}

The three-corpus worked example finds consistent directional excess
over the geometric null at the fixed $3\degr$ period and ${\sim}35.25\degr$E
Levantine corridor phase. The dome-excluded two-corpus combination (Wikidata + OSM) yields a Fisher
combination of $\chi^2(4) = \geoFisherNcAChi{}$, $p \geoFisherNcAP{}$ at Tier~A;
the all-three-corpus result (Fisher $p \geoFisherAPDisp{}$ at Tier~A)
includes the dome corpus and provides a less conservative cross-corpus summary than the dome-excluded combination.
All results are frame-conditional proximity-enrichment measures (see Limitations). The UNESCO corpus is
the most geographically distributed result, with A-tier sites spanning the full
Eurasian corridor.

Null~B (same-footprint restricted draw) provides the
discriminating comparison: among all UNESCO cultural sites
occupying the same longitude footprint, the dome/stupa subset shows
greater harmonic proximity than the broader background across all three
window widths after Bonferroni correction (see Results), illustrating
subset-specific enrichment within the shared geography. The cross-corpus
phase concordance (NPC $K \geq \npcDomeStupaK{}$ across all pairings of
three independently assembled monument datasets with different
geographic centers of mass) is consistent with the
phase not being an artifact of any single corpus's geographic
distribution: UNESCO dome sites, Wikidata Q180987 stupas, and OSM
stupa tags converge on the same ${\sim}35.25\degr$E phase independently
of one another.

\textbf{Corpus overlap and curation.}
The three corpora are assembled by distinct processes: the UNESCO
dome/stupa subset derives from keyword matching against the WHC XML
dataset; Wikidata Q180987 was extracted via SPARQL query on the
\textit{instance-of: stupa} property; OSM was assembled by
crowd-sourced tagging of \texttt{building=stupa},
\texttt{historic=stupa}, and \texttt{ruins=stupa} features via
Overpass API. An empirical overlap check using GPS proximity
(threshold $< 1$~km) and name-string matching finds 4 near-coincident
site pairs between UNESCO and Wikidata, 0 between UNESCO and OSM, and
1 between Wikidata and OSM (see supplementary overlap audit). Because
all three datasets are publicly available, the candidate frame is
handled as fixed across the empirical demonstration. The Fisher
combination is used as a consistency check across differently assembled
datasets. The geographic clusters of the three corpora are
substantially non-overlapping at the region
level: UNESCO dome sites span the full Eurasian corridor from the
Levant to Java; Wikidata is dominated by the Java/Sumatra node; OSM
coverage reflects crowd-sourced mapping density across South and
Southeast Asia. No single shared geographic cluster explains enrichment in all three corpora simultaneously.

The Wikidata result reflects the documented geographic concentration
of stupa construction at the Java/Borobudur node
\citep{miksic1990borobudur}: that cluster's position on a $3\degr$
harmonic is precisely the proximity structure the geometric-null test
is designed to detect, and the geographic concentration is part of the
documented corpus pattern rather than a confound to be removed.
Sites near one another in this corpus are near one another because
that is where Buddhist communities built stupas over centuries; they
represent a genuine place-specific building tradition, not duplicate
observations of a single spatial event. No standard archaeological
spatial analysis discards sites on the grounds that a community built
more than one structure in the same locale.
Removing the Java/Sumatra cluster would require applying the same logic
to every regional node, including the Levant, Sri Lanka, and mainland Southeast Asia.
At that point no corpus survives; the same arbitrary-threshold problem
that motivates retaining all clusters (Section~\ref{sec:framework}) applies
here. The relevant check is cross-corpus: the corpus overlap audit finds
only one near-coincident pair between Wikidata and OSM, so the OSM enrichment is not
a restatement of the same Borobudur sites under a different label.
The OSM result, assembled by a process with no relationship to UNESCO
or Wikidata curation, shows the same directional excess
($p = \geoOsmAP{}$ at Tier~A) and the same phase concordance with
Wikidata ($K = \npcOsmStupaK{}$) in the worked example.
Figure~\ref{fig:geo_trail}
shows all three corpora mapped against the $3\degr$ harmonic grid.

The interpretation follows \citet{silva2020statistical}'s distinction
between statistical structure and archaeological explanation.
Significance tests evaluate evidence against a null model;
archaeological explanation is developed from evidence independent of
the orientations themselves, including the wider archaeological record
and socio-historical context. The statistical pattern illustrated here
is compatible with several mechanisms. These include geographic
channeling by trade routes and river systems following the Eurasian
corridor, cultural diffusion patterns concentrating stupa construction
at historically dominant nodes \citep{sen2014silk}, and selection
effects in the UNESCO inscription process.
An exploratory positive finding is consistent with this: weighting
OWTRAD nodes by degree centrality (the number of route edges incident
to each node, as a proxy for hub importance) finds that the most
network-central cities fall near the $3\degr$ harmonic grid more
often than the uniform null predicts. If major route hubs and
hemispherical monuments are both concentrated along the same interior
Eurasian corridor, the harmonic proximity of each would be a shared
consequence of corridor geography rather than an independent proximity
result; disentangling these requires a geographic control outside the
corridor, which remains a target for future work.
Historical interpretations involving deliberate placement would
additionally require evidence for pre-modern continental longitude
determination at sub-degree precision
\citep{hunger2019mul, neugebauer1975history}. The contribution of the
present work is to establish what the directly matched statistical
test reports when applied to three differently assembled corpora.

\subsection{Limitations}

\noindent\textbf{Frame conditionality.}
All $p$-values in Table~\ref{tab:cross_corpus_geo} are conditional on
the fixed $3\degr$ period and ${\sim}35.25\degr$E Levantine corridor
phase (anchored to Mount Gerizim, $\GerizimLon\degr$E). All three
corpora are evaluated against this same frame. The results are therefore
corpus-level proximity-enrichment measures under that fixed frame and
should not be read as outcomes of an unconditional search over all
possible periods and anchors.

\noindent\textbf{Analysis sequence and exploratory scope.}
This paper is an exploratory methods contribution following
\citet{silva2020statistical}. Pre-registration is a standard for confirmatory
hypothesis tests; no registry exists for, and none is expected of,
open-data descriptive spatial analyses of this kind. The appropriate
sequence for exploratory work is to identify a statistical pattern in one
dataset and assess whether it appears consistently across independently
assembled datasets — which is what the dome-corpus sweep followed by the
Wikidata+OSM cross-check does. The Wikidata+OSM Fisher combination is the
primary cross-corpus summary precisely because it excludes the
period-motivating corpus; the three-corpus result is a less conservative
supplement. The asymmetry is fully disclosed and verifiable from the
published code.

\noindent\textbf{Anchor-sweep correction.}
The frame-conditional tests (Table~\ref{tab:cross_corpus_geo}) ask
whether proximity enrichment is present across corpora given the fixed
frame. The anchor-sweep correction asks a harder question: is this
anchor globally exceptional after correcting for the best of
\anchorSweepNanchors{} trial longitudes? The corrected $p = \anchorMaxPermP{}$
($z = \anchorMaxPermZ{}$, marginal) quantifies what the evidence would
look like under an unconstrained global search. The marginal corrected $p$
is a genuine limitation on the unconditional case: it is consistent with
the anchor having been selected, implicitly or explicitly, from a region of
longitude space that produces favorable proximity counts. The frame-conditional
$p$-values quantify enrichment given the fixed frame; they do not quantify how
exceptional that frame is.

\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}

This paper demonstrates the distinction between Rayleigh concentration
and thresholded harmonic proximity as descriptors of a modulo-$T$ phase
distribution: Rayleigh summarizes mean circular concentration, while
the geometric-null binomial tests thresholded proximity to any
harmonic under the benchmark $p_0 = 2d/T$. The period sweep illustrates
this distinction empirically, with Rayleigh-significant periods lacking
proximity enrichment and the enriched $3.0\degr$ period lacking
significant Rayleigh concentration. Applied under a fixed operational
frame, with fixed period, corridor phase, thresholds, and corpora, the
binomial framework finds a consistent corpus-level proximity
pattern across three hemispherical-monument datasets at the
$3\degr$ period and ${\sim}35.25\degr$E Levantine corridor phase.

Two qualifications contextualize these results, both detailed in the
Limitations section. The period emerged from the dome corpus sweep;
the Wikidata+OSM combination ($\chi^2(4) = \geoFisherNcAChi{}$,
$p \geoFisherNcAP{}$ at Tier~A) is the primary cross-corpus check
precisely because it excludes that corpus. The anchor-sweep-corrected
$p = \anchorMaxPermP{}$ quantifies what the evidence looks like under
an unconstrained global search, which is a harder question than the
frame-conditional one and is answered separately.

Following \citet{silva2020statistical}, the worked example is best read
as a descriptive spatial exercise. This paper is a methods contribution:
it introduces and validates the geometric-null binomial framework, and
uses three hemispherical-monument corpora as a worked example to
illustrate how the method behaves on real data. No confirmatory
historical judgement is made, and none is possible from these results
alone. The statistics report corpus-level proximity enrichment under a
fixed frame; they cannot identify causal or intentional relationships.
This is an open-data observational analysis: the datasets are publicly
available and every step is independently reproducible from the published
code and audit files. The evidentiary gap between ``sites are
disproportionately close to a $3\degr$ harmonic grid'' and ``sites were
placed with knowledge of that grid'' lies outside the scope of any
purely statistical test; such claims require independent archaeological
and socio-historical evidence that proximity statistics cannot supply.

The paper's contribution is the explicit demonstration
that Rayleigh concentration and geometric-null binomial proximity
can dissociate within the same corpus, while each statistic remains
useful for its own question. It also provides a reproducible open-data
example that future comparative work can evaluate.

All data, code, and audit files are openly available at Zenodo
(\citealt{tenenbaum2026audit};
\url{https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.20123709}).

